This Doc Spatz post is the ugliest thing that I have ever seen on this site.<br><br>
As a point of order, Doc, I believe that *I* posted before you on the site, if my archive download is correct.<br><br>
I thought I would &quot;quote-repost&quot; some of your more notable posts showing the literary evolution to what we now have confronting us, but, frankly, in light of you unbridled rage, I would be wasting my time.<br><br>
Instead, I am going to quote an early comment by a proud Vietnam Veteran to your first two posts in December, 1996:<br><br>
&quot;In response to Lear Pearson, Dr. Spatz and all protestors this is a quote from Samual Adams and it just seems to fit you all so well. In the eyes of this veteran you are all cowards.<br>
'If ye love wealth greater than liberty, the tranquility of servitude greater than the animating contest for freedom, go home from us in peace. We seek not your counsel nor your arms. Crouch down and lick the hand that feeds you and may posterity forget that ye were once our countrymen.'<br>
                                    — Samuel Adams&quot;<br><br>
There is a lot more. In fact, there are protestors who have posted here for whom I have the deepest respect and with whom I have debated, civilly, and with honor. Honor is very important to me as a Vietnam Veteran. I do not quite see it in this latest outburst of your temperment.<br><br>
Doc, face facts, *The PACK is Back*. This is the reality with which you must deal. It will not change, and you cannot change it. After all, this is a site concerning the Vietnam War, and we fought *in* it, not around it. Of course we have differing opinions. Here I am speaking quite civily as one who has endured your protestor *pack* for as long as everyone now posting, except for Chet and maybe Tom, real Tunkasilla. Why cannot you conduct yourself civily? I do not know. I don't really want to know. I now no longer care.<br><br>
You seem to have you back against the wall with Cook. That is between you and him. Are we playing favorites, as you suggest? Sure, we are. Cook is one of us. But too, so have you played favorites in the past. Us, you, them, it goes on forever.<br><br>
Here is my first post on #6, Protest:<br><br>
&quot;VIETNAM VETERAN'S PROTEST<br>
Mon Dec  2 23:37:19 US/Eastern 1996<br><br>
I have read all the posts in this section on protest.<br>
I respect those who personally chose to protest the Vietnam War but did not judge those whose personal choices resulted in combat. A debate of choices is the essence of democracy as guaranteed by the Constitution. I would be honored to debate those individuals.<br>
I do not respect those whose uninformed moral high ground judgement of those who fought in the Vietnam War is the essence or justification of their protest. No matter what examples are given in support of their position, the reception given to returning Vietnam War combatants by such minded people is validation of their lack of respect for the Constitution and the democratic process. These people are not worthy adversaries in debate.<br>
I am a Vietnam Veteran, and you may consider this my protest.   <br>
-- art16@ix.netcom.com  (Arthur Varanelli)&quot;<br><br>
And Doc, here is yours: <br><br>
&quot;HONOR THE PROTESTORS<br>
Sat Dec 14 15:56:31 US/Eastern 1996<br><br>
I stood up to screaming patriots, and burned my draft card.  I protested and marched, screamed and cried, told my generation to stop, don't go, this was was wrong.  I ended up a C.O. doing 2 years of bedpans, not smoking dope in canada.  I think that I, and those like me, are the true patriots, the true disenters, who tried to stop 50,000 of our generation from coming home in bags.  What did we achieve? NOTHING !  The Peace Movement was never that, it was just ,anti war, and when Nam ended, so did the movement.  No memorial wall, no etched names for the resistors, not even the God Damn GI Bill benefits, and I gave up 2 years of my life too.  When will America wake up and acknowledge that the protestors, SDS, and war resistors were right??  We don't need the McNamara confessions to validate us, but some serious acknowledgement of our being right would be nice.   Nam is a weight that I carry too.<br>
-- shrink4u@irvine.quik.com  (Dr.Barry Spatz)&quot;<br><br>
A blast from the past? There is a lot more, really. Go back to the beginning and think how far you have come. Not far? It is not surprising to me.<br><br>
Zounds! We are consistent! ...to a point. I stand on my record of having a meaningfull debate with protestors up on the unpublished FORUM and we parted with respect and honor. Not so here.<br><br>
Well, folks, Brothers of Choice, and fellow Vets, it is late. I do like being triggered this way, though. A soft challenge gives me a rest. <br><br>
See yawl tomorrow!<br><br>
